[1] Bangladesh (Dhaka)
Date: Wed 11 Jul 2007
Source: The Daily Star [edited]
<http://www.thedailystar.net/2007/07/11/d70711014724.htm>

Fears of a dengue outbreak are growing following the appearance of a
number of cases in the capital, Dhaka.
During the last couple of days [8, 9 Jul 2007], 8 people with dengue
symptoms have been admitted to Dhaka Medical College Hospital, Holy
Family Red Crescent Hospital, Ibn Sina Hospital, and Central
Hospital. However, 6 out of the 8 dengue-infected patients were
released from the hospitals.
The patients reside in the areas of PWD colony, Malibagh,
Mohammadpur, Tikatuli, Basabo, and Keraniganj.
According to Nasimus Siraj, chief entomologist of Dhaka City
Corporation (DCC), fumigation drives are on in the city to combat the
situation and the DCC is monitoring the situation.
DCC also intends to launch a mass awareness campaign to clean up all
areas in the city and destroy breeding places of dengue-bearing
mosquitoes. Volunteers and Boy Scouts have been requested to help the
DCC with the campaign, he added.
[Over the past] 6 years, Bangladesh has raised concerns over the
outbreak of dengue fever, which has killed 130 people. In 2006, 1423
people in Dhaka were infected with the disease and 4 of them died.
Warmer weather and heavy rains help the mosquito-borne virus spread
through the region. There is no treatment for dengue, which can cause
high fever, rash, headache, and severe muscle and joint pains. A more
severe form can cause [sometimes fatal] hemorrhagic fever.
_Aedes_, the dengue-carrying mosquito, breeds in stagnant water in
houses, construction sites, schools, and factories.
--
