[4] Cambodia
Date: Sat 14 Jul 2007
Source: Reuters UK [edited]
<http://uk.reuters.com/article/healthNews/idUKBKK3568020070714?pageNumber=1>

Dengue fever has killed 182 Cambodians so far this year [2007], and
the crisis will continue to worsen unless concerted community action
is taken, the government and World Health Organisation (WHO) said on
Saturday [14 Jul 2007].
"This year [2007] is particularly severe and, if present trends
continue, it will be the most serious to date," the WHO and the
Health Ministry said in a joint statement.
"Community-based larval control and elimination of mosquito breeding
sites are currently the only sustainable methods of outbreak
prevention and the only effective method of reducing the risk of
infection," the statement said.
Health officials had been working hard in anti-mosquito breeding
campaigns in high-risk areas since the outbreak, but the results were
not very satisfactory, Ngan Chantha, head of the country's anti-dengue
program, told Reuters. "It's hard to change our people's behavior.
Health workers can't do all the work, and villagers have to help
themselves, too," he said, telling Cambodians to clean containers
every 10 days to stem mosquito breeding.
The virus was expected to reach its peak during the late
August-September [2007] heavy rainy season, Ngan Chantha said.
Dengue has killed 182 out of 14 986 infected so far this year [2007],
compared with 116 deaths from 12 300 infected in the whole of 2006,
Ngan Chantha said.
--
